Before placing a high-risk AI system from a non-EU provider on the EU market, an importer must verify the following four key elements under **Article 23(1)** of the EU AI Act:

1. Conformity assessment: The provider has carried out the relevant conformity assessment procedure (**Article 43**).
 > the relevant conformity assessment procedure referred to in Article 43 has been carried out by the provider of the high-risk AI system;

2. Technical documentation: The provider has drawn up the technical documentation in accordance with **Article 11** and **Annex IV**.
 > the provider has drawn up the technical documentation in accordance with Article 11 and Annex IV;

3. CE marking and accompanying documents: The system bears the required CE marking, is accompanied by the EU declaration of conformity (**Article 47**), and includes instructions for use.
 > the system bears the required CE marking and is accompanied by the EU declaration of conformity referred to in Article 47 and instructions for use;

4. Authorised representative: The provider has appointed an authorised representative in the Union (**Article 22(1)**).
 > the provider has appointed an authorised representative in accordance with Article 22(1).

If the importer has sufficient reason to consider that any of these conditions is not met, or that the system or its documentation is falsified, it must not place the system on the market until conformity is restored (**Article 23(2)**). If the system presents a risk within the meaning of **Article 79(1)**, the importer must inform the provider, the authorised representative, and the market surveillance authorities.
